Part I - Dataset Exploration - Ford GoBikes.¶

by Timothy Babatunde¶

1. Introduction¶

This project has two parts that illustrates the importance and value of data visualization tools in the data analysis process. This is a Capstone project, part of the Udacity Data Analysis Nanodegree course.

In this part, I will use Python libraries to wrangle and explore a 201902-fordgobike-tripdata.csv datafile, starting from vieweing single variables to plots of multiple variables.

In the following second part of the project, I will produce a short presentation that illustrates interesting properties, trends, and relationships that I discovered in the cleaned dataset I exported.

1.1 Dataset and its origin¶

Bay Wheels is the Bay Area's regional bike share program serving Berkeley, Emeryville, Oakland, San Jose and San Francisco. Bay Wheels offers convenient, healthy, climate-friendly transportation around the Bay Area.

Bay Wheels offers over 7,000 bicycles (both traditional bikes and hybrid electric bikes) at 550 stations:

Pedal-powered bikes can be picked up and dropped off at Bay Wheels docking stations

E-bikes can use the docking stations or can be locked to a city bike rack

This data set includes information about individual rides made in a bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area during 1February 2019. The dataset can be downloaded here

The dataset has columns:¶

  • Duration_sec
  • Start_time
  • End_time
  • Start_station_id
  • Start_station_name
  • Start_station_latitude
  • Start_station_longitude
  • End_station_id
  • End_station_name
  • End_station_latitude
  • End_station_longitude
  • Bike_id
  • User_type
  • Member_birth_year
  • Member_gender
  • Bike_share_for_all_trip

Summary of identified Quality and Tidiness issues¶

Quality issues¶

  1. starttime and endtime have the wrong datatype string (in stead of datetime)

  2. user_type has wrong datatype string (in stead of categorical)

  3. Null Values in some columns

  4. Odd year for a row in member_birth_year

Tidiness issues¶
  1. Create column for duration_min, start day etc

Issue #5: Tidiness: Create column for duration_min, start day etc¶

Define:¶

  • To complete investigations, create column for duration_min, start day etc

Code¶

In [18]:
# Extract age, minute,day,week,month from the start_time
clean_bikes['duration_min'] = clean_bikes['duration_sec']/60

#Creating a variable for the base year
year = 2019

clean_bikes['Date'] = clean_bikes.start_time.dt.strftime('%Y-%m-%d')
clean_bikes['Hour_of_day'] = clean_bikes.start_time.dt.strftime('%H')
clean_bikes['Day_of_week'] = clean_bikes.start_time.dt.strftime('%A')
clean_bikes['Age'] = (year - clean_bikes['member_birth_year']).astype(int)

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

In this datast, there are 174951 unique trips, with their durations, start time, end time, start station id, end station id, start station name, end station name, bike id , user type, birth year and gender.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

When are the most trips taken, breaking into hour of the day or day of the week? Also, how does this differ between Customers and Subscribers?

Does the average duration of a bike trip depend on whether a user is a Subscriber or a Customer?

What bike station(s) is/are the most popular starting point and destination? Does this correlate with duration?

What age and gender rent bikes the most, and is there any relationship with these and the duration of the trip?

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

user_type trip_duration end_station_name start_time member_birth_year member_gender

# Creating a lineplot function.
def lineplot (x, y,  xlabel, ylabel, title):
    '''Plots a lineplot ofthe x and y axes
    x= Value of x axes
    y= Numeric data to represent the x axes
    xlabel = Label of X axes
    ylabel = Label of Y axes'''
    
    plt.figure(figsize=[20, 10])
    x= x
    y = y
    sb.lineplot(x, y)
    plt.xlabel(xlabel, size= 14)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel, size= 14)
    plt.title(title, size= 14)
    plt.show();

# Creats a subplot function that plots a variable against an integer 
def subplot(x, y, xlabel, ylabel, title):
    ''' Plots a subplot of the parsed data
    x = value of the x axes
    y = value of y axes
    xlabel =  Label of x axes
    ylabel = Label of Y axes
    title = Title of subplot'''
    
    figure= plt.figure(figsize=(12,9))
    plt.subplot(2,1,2)
    plt.bar(x.index , y.values)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel , size= 12)
    plt.xlabel(xlabel , size= 12)
    plt.title(title)
    plt.xticks(rotation = 85)

    figure.tight_layout(pad=3)

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

The number of occurrence of a particular type of feature does not determine the time spent of the feature, on the other hand Start stations and end stations does not determine the trip duration.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

In the Univariate Exploration, I found out that the male gender has more number of trips than other genders, I expected this to also be the relationship in duration of trips, this is not the case as the other genders have a take longer trip times than the male gender. This is also the same with subscribers and customers.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

Yes, in the Univariate exploration and bivariate, the subscribers had a higher number of trips than the customers, this was stengthened when broken down as all genders in subscribers had a higher number of trips than the customers.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

It is interesring to know that both user types spend more time on trips during the weekends. Also, the increase in stime spent by the Customers during weekends increases significantly.


6. Conclusions¶

The graphs reinforces the idea that more people tend to use bikes as a means of transportation on week days and the peak times are when they go to work and leave work, the use of bikes drastically reduces by weekends. (number)

Subscribers mainly hire a bike during weekdays (more than double the level of weekends), while for Customers, they hire relatively the same number of trips all week round.

It is very interesting to note that the duration of trips in the weekdays is significantly lower than on weekends in both the subscribers and Customers.

The average bike trip duration of Customers is about the double of Subscribers(21 to 10 mis).

Males subscribers spend more time on the road than other genders (other and females) but averagely, they spend less time on the road. This shows that most of the males durations fall in the lower spectrum.
